      <div xml:id="NA194-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu ciṟaippuṟamākac ceṟippaṟivuṟīiyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is how [he] is informed of [her] confinement while [he] is behind the fence.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA194">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            amma vāḻi tōḻi kaimmā</l>
<l>            ṟiyātucey vāṅko ṟāmē kayavāyk</l>
<l>            kaṉṟuṭai maruṅkiṟ piṭipuṇarn tiyalum</l>
<l>            valaṉuyar maruppi ṉilanīrt taṭakkai</l>
<l>            yaṇṇal yāṉaik kaṉṟiyuṅ kaṉmicait </l>
<l>            taṉinilai yitaṇam pulampap pōki</l>
<l>            mantiyu maṟiyā marampayi loruciṟaik</l>
<l>            kuṉṟa veṟpaṉoṭu nāmviḷai yāṭa</l>
<l>            virumpukavar koṇṭa vēṉaṟ</l>
<l>            peruṅkural koḷḷāc ciṟupacuṅ kiḷikkē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>        Alas, oh friend –</l>
<l>        what can we on our part do in exchange</l>
<l rend="indent">            for the small green parakeet that didn't take the big ear</l>
<l rend="indent">            of the millet, which has [now] been seized [and] taken by the iron [sickle],<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">virumpu kavar koṇṭa: kavar + koḷ</term> seem to be mutually enhancing quasi-synonyms here, while <term xml:lang="ta">virumpu</term>, "iron", must refer to the iron sickle used by the cutters to harvest the field, in other words the situation is that of reminiscence of passed happiness.</note></l>
<l rend="indent2">            while we were playing<note place="foot">Actually there is no tense notion at all in the infinite construction of line 8 and 10, but the idea of a reciprocal favour implies a notion of anteriority.</note> with the man from the hilly mountains</l>
<l rend="indent2">            on a site dense with trees not even known to the she-monkey,</l>
<l rend="indent3">            going solitarily for the platform standing on stony height,</l>
<l>            alone except for the excellent elephant<note place="foot">Here we either have to read <term xml:lang="ta">yāṉaikk’ aṉṟiyum ... taṉi nilai</term> or else <term xml:lang="ta">yāṉaikk’ aṉṟiyum ... mantiyum aṟiyā</term>, slightly awkward in both cases because of the dative marking.</note> with water</l>
<l rend="indent2">            from the ground<note place="foot">Here one is sorely tempted to emend <term xml:lang="ta">nilam nīr</term> into <term xml:lang="ta">iḷam nīr</term> (which would only mean changing the liquid into the retroflex), since "water from the ground" does not seem very convincing, while "fresh water" would be formulaic.</note> in [his] long trunk, with strong upright tusks,</l>
<l rend="indent2">            that moves forward together with [his] female which has at [her] side<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kaṉṟ’ uṭai maruṅkiṉ</term>: this looks like a very awkward redundancy, if not an inaccuracy in the transmission of the text.</note></l>
<l rend="indent4">                a soft-mouthed calf.</l>
        </lg>
         </div>
